<div class="page-header">
        <div class="row"><h2 class="col-md-8 col-md-offset-2 center">Core Concepts</h2></div>
        
        
<div style="border-top: 1px solid #DDD; padding-top:21px;">
          <div class="row"><div class="col-md-8 col-md-offset-2 justify"><em><p>A brief overview of the primary objects or "resources" within&nbsp;Intellinote.</p>
<p>This document is <em>not</em> a data-dictionary nor a comprehensive technical&nbsp;reference.</p>
<p>It <em>is</em> an introduction to some of the core concepts you'll encounter within the Intellinote API, intended to help you better understand and navigate the Intellinote&nbsp;framework.</p>
</em></div></div>
        </div>
        
</div>
    
    
<div class="row">
      <div class="col-md-12">
        <div style="text-align:center; border-bottom: 1px solid #DDD; padding-bottom:21px;"><a href="#users">Users</a> | <a href="#notes">Notes</a> | <a href="#workspaces">Workspaces</a> | <a href="#organizations">Organizations</a></div>

<div align="center">
<br>
<img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="entity relationship diagram">
<br><br>
<p><i style="color:#666">Relationships between several core entities within Intellinote.</i></p>
</div>


<h2 id="users">Users</h2>
<p>A <strong><em>user</em></strong> is an account within Intellinote.</p>
<p><em>Users</em> have a handful of common attributes, including:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>user_id</code> - an arbitrary, unique identifier for the <em>user</em> (assigned).</li>
<li><code>given_name</code> - first name (required).</li>
<li><code>family_name</code> - last name (required).</li>
<li><code>email</code> - email address (required).</li>
<li><code>title</code> - job title (optional).</li>
<li><code>tel_work</code> - work phone (optional).</li>
<li><code>tel_cell</code> - mobile phone (optional).</li>
<li><code>avatar</code> - URL of the user's avatar image.</li>
</ul>
<p>Intellinote <em>user</em> attributes are inspired by and largely compatible
with the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/VCard">vCard</a> standard.</p>
<h2 id="notes">Notes</h2>
<p>A <strong><em>note</em></strong> is the fundamental unit of content within Intellinote.</p>
<p><em>Notes</em> have several core attributes, including:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>note_id</code> - an arbitrary, unique identifier for the <em>note</em> (assigned).</li>
<li><code>title</code> - a label or subject for the <em>note</em> (optional).</li>
<li><code>body</code> - the text of the <em>note</em> (optional).</li>
<li><code>note_type</code> - the kind or sub-type of note, such as "task" (required).</li>
</ul>
<p>Intellinote defines several kinds of <em>note</em>, such as NOTEs, TASKs, CHATs, RESOURCEs (files) and REPLYs (comments). These are distinguished by the <code>note_type</code> attribute.</p>
<p>Different types of <em>note</em> may include additional attributes.  For example, a <em>task</em> is a <em>note</em> that includes attributes for tracking to whom a task is assigned and when the task is due.</p>
<p><em>Notes</em> often have:</p>
<ul>
<li><em>attachments</em> - documents or files associated with the <em>note</em></li>
<li><em>replies</em> - a comment attached to the <em>note</em>, and</li>
<li><em>tags</em> - free-text labels, keywords or categories used to organize <em>notes</em> in a type of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Folksonomy">folksonomy</a>.</li>
</ul>
<p>(The Intellinote API and this documentation sometimes use the term "note" to refer to all <em>note</em> types generically.)</p>
<h2 id="workspaces">Workspaces</h2>
<p>A <strong><em>workspace</em></strong> provides a place for one or more <em>users</em> to create, share and collaborate around <em>notes</em> (of all types).</p>
<p>Each <em>workspace</em> defines a small number of core attributes, including:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>workspace_id</code> - an arbitrary, unique identifier for the <em>workspace</em> (assigned).</li>
<li><code>name</code> - a label or title for the <em>workspace</em> (required).</li>
<li><code>description</code> - a brief summary of the goal or intent behind the <em>workspace</em> (optional).</li>
</ul>
<p>Every <em>note</em> belongs to exactly one <em>workspace</em>.  (A <em>workspace</em> can, of course, contain many <em>notes</em>.)</p>
<p><em>Workspaces</em> contain one or more <em>users</em>, called "members".  Members may have different levels of access to a <em>workspace</em>, depending upon their specific "role".</p>
<p>Every <em>workspace</em> belongs to exactly one <em>organization</em>.</p>
<h2 id="organizations">Organizations</h2>
<p>An <strong><em>organization</em></strong> is a collection of <em>users</em> and <em>workspaces</em>.</p>
<p><em>Organizations</em> have a small number of core attributes:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>org_id</code> - an arbitrary, unique identifier for the <em>organization</em> (assigned).</li>
<li><code>name</code> - a label or title for the <em>organization</em> (required).</li>
</ul>
<p><em>Organizations</em> contain zero or more <em>workspaces</em>.</p>
<p><em>Organizations</em> contain one or more <em>users</em>, called "members".  Members may have different levels of access to an <em>organization</em> and the <em>workspaces</em> within it, depending upon their specific "role".</p>
